> Hi Grant, Great to hear the asbestos report came back =
clear=E2=80=94fantastic news! I'm happy for Asset Restore to begin the =
initial fire and smoke clean. I=E2=80=99m available to meet them at the =
property tomorrow (Tuesday) before 8 am (you can reach me at
> =20
> Hi Grant,
>=20
> Great to hear the asbestos report came back clear=E2=80=94fantastic =
news! I'm happy for Asset Restore to begin the initial fire and smoke =
clean. I=E2=80=99m available to meet them at the property tomorrow =
(Tuesday) before 8=E2=80=AFam (you can reach me at 0275089102), or on =
Wednesday anytime before 11=E2=80=AFam.
>=20
> Just a quick reminder regarding the contents insurance: As discussed =
with Chris, I=E2=80=99ve removed several items from the property =
following the fire=E2=80=94particularly electronics and lithium-powered =
devices, which could present a safety risk. Could you please advise on =
the next steps for assessing these?
>=20
> Lastly, regarding the Assessment-Only Focus, I=E2=80=99m unclear on =
what =E2=80=9CThis will occur as per process=E2=80=9D means. Could you =
clarify what the process entails?
>=20
> Kind regards,
> Raffaella
>=20
> =20
>=20
> =20
>=20
> On 14 Jul 2025, at 3:21=E2=80=AFPM, Grant Metson =
<Grant.Metson@tower.co.nz <mailto:Grant.Metson@tower.co.nz>> wrote:
> =20
> Hi Rafaella,
> Please find attached for your records a copy of the Asbestos Survey =
which we have just received.
> There was no asbestos found to be present within the structure, the =
surrounds, the contents or any of the debris.
> We are now ready to move onto the next stage in the process which will =
be to undertake and complete as follows:
> =20
> Contents Appraisal
> Contents Removal
> Full decontamination clean upstairs level.
> Strip-out dwelling to provide visibility for scope of works
> All of the stages/processes listed above can be completed in =
chronological order as above, by Asset Restore.
> =20
> Below I have provided answers in blue to your recent questions. Which =
I trust will allow us to move forward with the claim progression. =20
> =20
> Clarify Claim Scope: Is this the plan for both house and contents =
claims? If so, should it therefore be linked to both policy numbers to =
ensure all coverage is included? The structural claim will require a =
scope -of works which is identified in the process list. The contents =
claim will have a schedule of contents determined. This is also listed I =
the process list provided. The 2 do not need to be linked. They can be =
cross referenced if needed. =20
> Prioritize Health & Safety: I=E2=80=99d feel more comfortable if we =
scheduled independent assessments (electrical, structural, gas, =
moisture/mould) before any major work, alongside the July 9 asbestos =
survey. The master electrician=E2=80=99s finding that the property is =
uninhabitable due to electrical hazards is a key concern. This can all =
be scheduled now that we have asbestos clearance. Do you want me to =
schedule this to occur ASAP?
> Assessment-Only Focus: As previously expressed, could we limit initial =
tasks to enabling damage assessment (e.g., securing the site, debris =
removal) rather than repairs (e.g., upstairs decontamination, curtain =
cleaning)? This would allow for a thorough evaluation and mutual =
agreement on remediation. The planned upstairs cleaning (July 21-25) =
feels premature for these reasons:
> We need to assess damage before repair to preserve evidence. This will =
occur as per process.=20
> If the gas unit (likely damaged) requires removal, the ceiling may =
need cutting, necessitating re-cleaning. Yes =E2=80=93 but this will =
form part of the repair process. It all needs to be assessed first. =20
> The electrician=E2=80=99s uninhabitable ruling requires electrical =
work first. This will occur as per process. =20
> Firefighters switched off water (possibly gas?) and electricity, which =
must be assessed and remediated. This will occur as per process. =20
> With 4 pets and hybrid work, noisy basement/deck/roof work makes =
living there untenable until completed. That is your decision when you =
choose to re-occupy. There is no pressure from your insurer to do so.
> Asbestos Survey Details: While I=E2=80=99m supportive of the July 9 =
survey, could you please share who will conduct it, the scope and tests =
involved, and how I can independently verify the results? Also, can the =
funding for this be covered under the claim preparation =
provision?Provided and shared with you.
> Structural Engineer Guidelines: I previously asked about guidelines =
for paying a structural engineer, as per the provision for claim =
preparation. Could you please provide these, as I believe an independent =
assessment should precede any repair work? Agreed. It will precede =
repair work =E2=80=93 but the site must be cleaned and cleared first so =
the structure can be properly assessed. =20
> One of the things I should underline is that with any claim of this =
nature there are multiple cleaning processes which occur =E2=80=93 these =
are normally as follows:
> =20
> Initial fire/smoke clean: to allow for detailed and accurate =
structural assessment. To reduce smoke and other claim related odors. To =
prevent further contamination and spreading of soot, etc.
> Subsequent and multiple site cleans during repair works: this is a =
constant process of keeping the site tidy.
> Final professional clean: this is completed before the home is =
re-occupied.
> =20
> My apologies =E2=80=93 I was not clear enough to explain that the =
cleaning process is not singular and final =E2=80=93 it is part of an =
ongoing process as described above.
> =20
> Please let me know when we can issue instructions for Asset Managers =
to continue with the next steps in the process provided.
> Best Regards,
> Grant.=20
>   =20
